  <section id="limitations">
    <h2>Limitations & Extreme Challenges</h2>
    <p>
      GraphCore theory outlines optimal scenarios. In practicality, engineering this processor relies on overcoming extreme physical thresholds:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Spectral Crosstalk:</strong> High-density light interference in adjacent waveguides will severely cross-contaminate state purity, forcing erroneous optical shifts.</li>
      <li><strong>Phase Drift & Coherence Loss:</strong> Thermal variances occurring dynamically during computation will warp index refraction slightly, degrading the precise definition of specific <code>φ</code> indices.</li>
      <li><strong>Optical Noise:</strong> Base electron scatter inherently trapped in the graphene lattice will generate random wavelength spikes, corrupting local logical states.</li>
      <li><strong>Manufacturing Yield Constraints:</strong> Nanoscale fabrication scaling capable of enforcing pure deterministic graphene edges currently exceeds general commercial abilities.</li>
      <li><strong>Alignment Sensitivity:</strong> System interfacing between classical digital IO peripherals and light-based array entry points demands micron-level alignment stability across all thermal envelopes.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

